HEADWORD: Pibroch
<hw>Pi"broch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gael.
<ets>piobaireachd</ets> pipe music, fr. <ets>piobair</ets> a piper, fr.
<ets>pioba</ets> pipe, bagpipe, from English. See <er>Pipe</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>A Highland air, suited to the particular
passion which the musician would either excite or assuage; generally
applied to those airs that are played on the bagpipe before the
Highlanders when they go out to battle.</def>
<rj><au>Jamieson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

